      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":334,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":354,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very gently, let the body wake up. Focus on relaxed breathing and upright posture.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Maintain conversational pace throughout. Heart rate should stay below 75% max HR (~143 bpm). This is aerobic base work — resist the urge to push.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":354,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gradually slow to a walk. Shake out legs and do light dynamic stretching post-run.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of very easy jogging or brisk walking to ease into the effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes, then stretch calves, hip flexors, and hamstrings for 5–10 minutes.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This easy run builds your aerobic base without adding fatigue. After a solid week of 60 km, we keep Tuesday light and controlled. Run by feel — if 5:04/km feels hard today, slow down to 5:30+. Easy days are the foundation of marathon fitness.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Lactate Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":57,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":252,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy jog at 5:04–5:34/km. Include 4 x 20-second strides in the final 2 minutes to prime the legs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":33,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"8 km continuous at threshold pace (4:12/km). This should feel 'comfortably hard' — you can speak in short phrases but not hold a conversation. Aim for even splits. If you drift more than 5 sec/km off pace, ease back slightly.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy jog back to full recovery. Let heart rate drop below 130 bpm before stopping.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog. In the last 400m of warmup, run 2 x 20-second pickups at tempo effort to prime your lactate system.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 km easy jog. Follow with calf raises, hip flexor stretches, and foam rolling if available.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold running at 4:12/km raises your lactate threshold — the cornerstone of marathon performance. We've stepped the tempo segment up from 6 km to 8 km this week, a natural progression from your recent training. Keep effort steady and even; negative splitting is fine but don't start too fast.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals — 5 x 1200m\",\"target_distance_km\":14,\"target_duration_minutes\":60,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":234,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy jog. Include 4 x 20-second strides at the end to activate fast-twitch fibres before the intervals begin.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":6,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":234,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 1200m at interval pace (3:54/km). Each rep should feel hard but controlled — you should finish each one feeling like you could do one more. Do NOT sprint. Consistent pacing across all 5 reps is the goal.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"400m jog recovery between each interval (~2:30–3:00 min). Keep moving — do not stop completely. Heart rate should drop to ~120–130 bpm before starting the next rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2–3 km easy jog. Shake out the legs and let your breathing fully normalise.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog followed by dynamic drills (leg swings, high knees, butt kicks) and 4 x 20-second strides.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2–3 km easy jog. Stretch quads, hamstrings, calves thoroughly. Prioritise hydration and a light snack within 30 minutes.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"We're progressing from 6 x 1km to 5 x 1200m — same total quality volume but longer reps that better simulate sustained race effort. VO2Max intervals develop your aerobic ceiling, which ultimately raises all your training paces. Saturday gives you a full day of rest before Sunday's long run, so push confidently here.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Run with Marathon Pace Finish\",\"target_distance_km\":27,\"target_duration_minutes\":148,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":354,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 2 km very easy — treat this as a moving warmup. Let the body settle in before finding your long run rhythm.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":110,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run km 3 through km 22 at easy long run pace (5:04–5:34/km). Focus on relaxed form, steady breathing, and fuelling every 45 minutes. This is aerobic conditioning — do not drift faster than 5:04/km.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":18,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 4 km at marathon pace (4:28/km). This teaches your body to run goal pace on tired legs — a critical marathon-specific stimulus. Stay smooth and controlled; do not race this section.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 1 km walk/jog to bring heart rate down. Do not stop abruptly after the marathon pace section.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start very easy for the first 2 km. No need for formal warmup drills — the first portion of the long run serves as the warmup.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes. Prioritise post-run nutrition within 30–45 minutes (carbohydrate + protein). Stretch and elevate legs if possible.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is the centrepiece of your week. At 27 km, we've added 1 km to last week's long run — within the 10% progression rule. The final 4 km at marathon pace (4:28/km) is a powerful stimulus: it trains your neuromuscular system and metabolic pathways to sustain goal pace when fatigued. Fuel during the run — aim for 30–60g of carbohydrate per hour from km 45 onward. This is a big day; respect it.\",\"perceived_effort\":7}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "modelId": "\"claude-sonnet-4-6\"",
